[src:fsr-upscaling/anti-aliasing] In cel animation, animators can either add motion lines or create an object trail to give the impression of movement.
[src:fsr-upscaling/anti-aliasing] To solve the wagon-wheel effect without changing the sampling rate or wheel speed, animators could add a broken or discolored spoke to force viewer's visual system to make the correct connections between frames.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] GPUOpen was announced on December 15, 2015, and released on January 26, 2016.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] He says that upcoming architectures, such as AMD's RX 400 series "include many features not exposed today in PC graphics APIs".
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] AMD designed GPUOpen to be a competing open-source middleware stack released under the MIT License.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] The libraries are intended to increase software portability between video game consoles, PCs and also high-performance computing.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] GPUOpen unifies many of AMD's previously separate tools and solutions into one package, also fully open-sourcing them under the MIT License.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] GPUOpen also makes it easy for developers to get low-level GPU access.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] Additionally AMD wants to grant interested developers the kind of low-level "direct access" to their GCN-based GPUs, that surpasses the possibilities of Direct3D 12 or Vulkan.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] AMD mentioned e.g. a low-level access to the Asynchronous Compute Engines (ACEs).
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] The ACE implement "Asynchronous Compute", but they cannot be freely configured under either Vulkan or Direct3D 12.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] GPUOpen is made up of several main components, tools, and SDKs.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] Software for computer-generated imagery (CGI) used in development of computer games and movies alike.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] The standard presets for FSR by AMD can be found in the table below.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] Note that these presets are not the only way in which the algorithm can be used, they are simply presets for input/output resolutions.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] Certain titles, such as *Dota 2*, offer resolution sliders to fine tune the scaling percentage or dynamically scaling the internal render resolution depending on the FPS cap.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] AMD has also created a command-line interface tool which allows the user to upscale any image using FSR1/EASU as in addition to other upsampling methods such as bilinear interpolation.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] It also allows the user to run various stages of the FSR pipeline, such as RCAS, independently.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] FSR 2 can also be modded into nearly any game supporting DLSS by swapping the DLSS DLL with a translation layer DLL that maps the DLSS API calls to FSR 2 API calls.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] The algorithm does not necessarily need to be implemented using these presets; it is possible for the implementer to define custom input and output resolutions.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] The linear scale factor used for upsampling the input resolution to the output resolution.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] For example, a scene rendered at 540p with a 2.00x scale factor would have an output resolution of 1080p.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] The linear render scale, compared to the output resolution, that the technology uses to render scenes internally before upsampling.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] For example, a 1080p scene with a 50% render scale would have an internal resolution of 540p.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] FSR 3 adds frame generation, a technique that creates new frames in between existing ones by using motion interpolation.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] Launching in September 2023, FSR 3 uses a combination of FSR 2 and optical flow analysis, which runs using asynchronous compute (as opposed to Nvidia's DLSS 3 which uses dedicated hardware).
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] Because FSR 3 uses a software-based solution, it is compatible with GPUs from AMD, Nvidia, and Intel as well as the ninth generation of video game consoles.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] To combat additional latency inherent to the frame generation process, AMD has a driver-level feature called Anti-Lag, which only runs on AMD GPUs.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] FSR “Redstone” adds a machine learning-based approach to generate frames.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] AMD Fluid Motion Frames (AFMF) is a driver-level frame generation technology launching in Q1 2024 which is compatible with all DirectX 11 and DirectX 12 games, however it runs on RDNA 2 and RDNA 3 GPUs.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] AFMF uses optical flow analysis but not motion vectors, so it can only interpolate a new frame between two traditionally rendered frames.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] AFMF currently is not compatible with VSYNC.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] Having been released by ATI Technologies under the BSD license in 2006 HLSL2GLSL is not part of GPUOpen.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] Whether similar tools for SPIR-V will be available remains to be seen, as is the official release of the Vulkan (API) itself.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] Source-code that has been defined as being part of GPUOpen is also part of the Linux kernel (e.g. amdgpu and amdkfd), Mesa 3D and LLVM.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] As of 2022, AMD compute software ecosystem is regrouped under the ROCm metaproject.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] AMD's "Boltzmann Initiative" (named after Ludwig Boltzmann) was announced in November 2015 at the SuperComputing15 and productized as the Radeon Open Compute platform (ROCm).
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] It aims to provide an alternative to Nvidia's CUDA which includes a tool to port CUDA source-code to portable (HIP) source-code which can be compiled on both HCC and NVCC.
[src:fsr-upscaling/fidelityfx] GPUOpen are available under the MIT license to the general public through GitHub starting on January 26, 2016.
