[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] In computer graphics and digital imaging, **image scaling** is the resizing of a digital image.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] In video technology, the magnification of digital material is known as upscaling or resolution enhancement.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] When scaling a vector graphic image, the graphic primitives that make up the image can be rendered using geometric transformations at any resolution with no loss of image quality.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] When scaling a raster graphics image, a new image with a higher or lower number of pixels must be generated.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] In the case of decreasing the pixel number (scaling down), this usually results in a visible quality loss.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] From the standpoint of digital signal processing, the scaling of raster graphics is a two-dimensional example of sample-rate conversion, the conversion of a discrete signal from a sampling rate (in this case, the local sampling rate) to another.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Image scaling can be interpreted as a form of image resampling or image reconstruction from the view of the Nyquist sampling theorem.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] According to the theorem, downsampling to a smaller image from a higher-resolution original can only be carried out after applying a suitable 2D anti-aliasing filter to prevent aliasing artifacts.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] The image is reduced to the information that can be carried by the smaller image.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] In the case of up sampling, a reconstruction filter takes the place of the anti-aliasing filter.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] A more sophisticated approach to upscaling treats the problem as an inverse problem, solving the question of generating a plausible image that, when scaled down, would look like the input image.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] A variety of techniques have been applied for this, including optimization techniques with regularization terms and the use of machine learning from examples.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] An image size can be changed in several ways.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] One of the simpler ways of increasing image size is nearest-neighbor interpolation, replacing every pixel with the nearest pixel in the output; for upscaling, this means multiple pixels of the same color will be present.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] This can preserve sharp details but also introduce jaggedness in previously smooth images.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] 'Nearest' in nearest-neighbor does not have to be the mathematical nearest.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] One common implementation is to always round toward zero.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Rounding this way produces fewer artifacts and is faster to calculate.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] This algorithm is often preferred for images which have little to no smooth edges.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] A common application of this can be found in pixel art.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Bilinear interpolation works by interpolating pixel color values, introducing a continuous transition into the output even where the original material has discrete transitions.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Although this is desirable for continuous-tone images, this algorithm reduces contrast (sharp edges) in a way that may be undesirable for line art.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Bicubic interpolation yields substantially better results, with an increase in computational cost.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Sinc resampling, in theory, provides the best possible reconstruction for a perfectly bandlimited signal.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] In practice, the assumptions behind sinc resampling are not completely met by real-world digital images.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Lanczos resampling, an approximation to the sinc method, yields better results.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Bicubic interpolation can be regarded as a computationally efficient approximation to Lanczos resampling.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] One weakness of bilinear, bicubic, and related algorithms is that they sample a specific number of pixels.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] When downscaling below a certain threshold, such as more than twice for all bi-sampling algorithms, the algorithms will sample non-adjacent pixels, which results in both losing data and rough results.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] The trivial solution to this issue is box sampling, which is to consider the target pixel a box on the original image and sample all pixels inside the box.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] This ensures that all input pixels contribute to the output.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] The major weakness of this algorithm is that it is hard to optimize.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Another solution to the downscale problem of bi-sampling scaling is mipmaps.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] A mipmap is a prescaled set of downscaled copies.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] When downscaling, the nearest larger mipmap is used as the origin to ensure no scaling below the useful threshold of bilinear scaling.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] This algorithm is fast and easy to optimize.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] It is standard in many frameworks, such as OpenGL.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] The cost is using more image memory, exactly one-third more in the standard implementation.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Simple interpolation based on the Fourier transform pads the frequency domain with zero components (a smooth window-based approach would reduce the ringing).
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Besides the good conservation (or recovery) of details, notable are the ringing and the circular bleeding of content from the left border to the right border (and the other way around).
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Edge-directed interpolation algorithms aim to preserve edges in the image after scaling, unlike other algorithms, which can introduce staircase artifacts.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Examples of algorithms for this task include New Edge-Directed Interpolation (NEDI), Edge-Guided Image Interpolation (EGGI), Iterative Curvature-Based Interpolation (ICBI), and Directional Cubic Convolution Interpolation (DCCI).
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] A 2013 analysis found that DCCI had the best scores in peak signal-to-noise ratio and structural similarity on a series of test images.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] For magnifying computer graphics with low resolution and/or few colors (usually from 2 to 256 colors), better results can be achieved by hqx or other pixel-art scaling algorithms.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] These produce sharp edges and maintain a high level of detail.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Vector extraction, or vectorization, offers another approach.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Vectorization first creates a resolution-independent vector representation of the graphic to be scaled.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] The resulting SVG vector file can then be exported and rendered at any required resolution without quality loss, serving directly as production-ready artwork for scalable display & printing.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] This technique is used by Adobe Illustrator, Live Trace, and Inkscape.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Scalable Vector Graphics are well suited to simple geometric images, while photographs do not fare well with vectorization due to their complexity.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] This method uses machine learning for more detailed images, such as photographs and complex artwork.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Programs that use this method include waifu2x, Imglarger and Neural Enhance.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] AI-driven upscaling software allows detail and sharpness to be added to historical photographs, where it is not present in the original.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] The availability of AI upscaling tools has led to confusion where a person believes that the upscaled version of a blurry image is genuinely showing them the subject of the original photograph.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] In 2025 a user of the social media site X posted an AI-upscaled version of a low resolution photo of Donald Trump that they had zoomed in on, and asked if anyone could "explain what the hell is happening to his forehead".
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Experts noted that the image had been distorted by the upscaling process, and that such tools "inevitably have to invent, or at least recreate, details that were or were not there".
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Image scaling is used in, among other applications, web browsers, image editors, image and file viewers, software magnifiers, digital zoom, the process of generating thumbnail images, and when outputting images through screens or printers.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] This application is the magnification of images for home theaters for HDTV-ready output devices from PAL-Resolution content, for example, from a DVD player.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Upscaling is performed in real time, and the output signal is not saved.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] As pixel-art graphics are usually low-resolution, they rely on careful placement of individual pixels, often with a limited palette of colors.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] This results in graphics that rely on stylized visual cues to define complex shapes with little resolution, down to individual pixels.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] This makes scaling pixel art a particularly difficult problem.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Specialized algorithms were developed to handle pixel-art graphics, as the traditional scaling algorithms do not take perceptual cues into account.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Since a typical application is to improve the appearance of fourth-generation and earlier video games on arcade and console emulators, many are designed to run in real time for small input images at 60 frames per second.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] On fast hardware, these algorithms are suitable for gaming and other real-time image processing.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] These algorithms provide sharp, crisp graphics, while minimizing blur.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Scaling art algorithms have been implemented in a wide range of emulators such as HqMAME and DOSBox, as well as 2D game engines and game engine recreations such as ScummVM.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] They gained recognition with gamers, for whom these technologies encouraged a revival of 1980s and 1990s gaming experiences.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Such filters are currently used in commercial emulators on Xbox Live, Virtual Console, and PSN to allow classic low-resolution games to be more visually appealing on modern HD displays.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Recently released games that incorporate these filters include *Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection*, *Castlevania: The Dracula X Chronicles*, *Castlevania: Symphony of the Night*, and *Akumajō Dracula X Chi no Rondo*.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] A number of companies have developed techniques to upscale video frames in real-time, such as when they are drawn on screen in a video game.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Nvidia's deep learning super sampling (DLSS) uses deep learning to upsample lower-resolution images to a higher resolution for display on higher-resolution computer monitors.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] AMD's FidelityFX Super Resolution 1.0 (FSR) does not employ machine learning, instead using traditional hand-written algorithms to achieve spatial upscaling on traditional shading units.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] FSR 2.0 utilises temporal upscaling, again with a hand-tuned algorithm.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] FSR standardized presets are not enforced, and some titles such as *Dota 2* offer resolution sliders.
[src:fsr-upscaling/image-scaling] Other technologies include Intel XeSS and Nvidia Image Scaler (NIS).
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] equal to 1 (top), 2 (middle) and 3 (bottom).
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] Also shown are two copies of the Lanczos kernel, shifted and scaled, corresponding to samples 4 and 11 (dashed curves).
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] Lanczos resampling is typically used to increase the sampling rate of a digital signal, or to shift it by a fraction of the sampling interval.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] It is often used also for multivariate interpolation, for example to resize or rotate a digital image.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] It has been considered the "best compromise" among several simple filters for this purpose.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] The filter was invented by Claude Duchon, who named it after Cornelius Lanczos due to Duchon's use of the sigma approximation in constructing the filter, a technique created by Lanczos.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] The effect of each input sample on the interpolated values is defined by the filter's reconstruction kernel *L*(*x*), called the Lanczos kernel.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] It is the normalized sinc function sinc(*x*), windowed (multiplied) by the **Lanczos window**, or **sinc window**, which is the central lobe of a horizontally stretched sinc function sinc(*x*/*a*) for −*a* ≤ *x* ≤ *a*.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] The parameter *a* is a positive integer, typically 2 or 3, which determines the size of the kernel.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] The Lanczos kernel has 2*a* − 1 lobes: a positive one at the center, and *a* − 1 alternating negative and positive lobes on each side.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] where *a* is the filter size parameter, and $\lfloor x\rfloor$ is the floor function.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] The bounds of this sum are such that the kernel is zero outside of them.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] As long as the parameter *a* is a positive integer, the Lanczos kernel is continuous everywhere, and its derivative is defined and continuous everywhere (even at *x* = ±*a*, where both sinc functions go to zero).
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] Therefore, the reconstructed signal *S*(*x*) too will be continuous, with continuous derivative.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] The Lanczos kernel is zero at every integer argument *x*, except at *x* = 0, where it has value 1.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] Therefore, the reconstructed signal exactly interpolates the given samples: we will have *S*(*x*) = *s**i* for every integer argument *x* = *i*.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] Lanczos resampling is one form of a general method developed by Lanczos to counteract the Gibbs phenomenon by multiplying coefficients of a truncated Fourier series by $\mathrm {sinc} (\pi k/m)$ , where k is the coefficient index and m is how many coefficients we're keeping.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] The same reasoning applies in the case of truncated functions if we wish to remove Gibbs oscillations in their spectrum.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] The theoretically optimal reconstruction filter for band-limited signals is the sinc filter, which has infinite support.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] The Lanczos filter is one of many practical (finitely supported) approximations of the sinc filter.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] Each interpolated value is the weighted sum of 2*a* consecutive input samples.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] Thus, by varying the 2*a* parameter one may trade computation speed for improved frequency response.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] The parameter also allows one to choose between a smoother interpolation or a preservation of sharp transients in the data.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] For image processing, the trade-off is between the reduction of aliasing artefacts and the preservation of sharp edges.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] Also as with any such processing, there are no results for the borders of the image.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] Increasing the length of the kernel increases the cropping of the edges of the image.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] The Lanczos filter has been compared with other interpolation methods for discrete signals, particularly other windowed versions of the sinc filter.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] Lanczos interpolation is a popular filter for "upscaling" videos in various media utilities, such as AviSynth and FFmpeg.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] Since the kernel assumes negative values for *a* > 1, the interpolated signal can be negative even if all samples are positive.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] More generally, the range of values of the interpolated signal may be wider than the range spanned by the discrete sample values.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] In particular, there may be ringing artifacts just before and after abrupt changes in the sample values, which may lead to clipping artifacts.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] However, these effects are reduced compared to the (non-windowed) sinc filter.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] For *a* = 2 (a three-lobed kernel) the ringing is < 1%.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] When using the Lanczos filter for image resampling, the ringing effect will create light and dark halos along any strong edges.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] While these bands may be visually annoying, they help increase the perceived sharpness, and therefore provide a form of edge enhancement.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] This may improve the subjective quality of the image, given the special role of edge sharpness in vision.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] In some applications, the low-end clipping artifacts can be ameliorated by transforming the data to a logarithmic domain prior to filtering.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] In this case the interpolated values will be a weighted geometric mean, rather than an arithmetic mean, of the input samples.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] The Lanczos kernel does not have the partition of unity property.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] That is, the sum ${\textstyle U(x)=\sum _{i\in \mathbb {Z} }L(x-i)}$ of all integer-translated copies of the kernel is not always 1.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] Therefore, the Lanczos interpolation of a discrete signal with constant samples does not yield a constant function.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] This defect is most evident when *a* = 1.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] Also, for *a* = 1 the interpolated signal has zero derivative at every integer argument.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] This is rather academic, since using a single-lobe kernel (*a* = 1) loses all the benefits of the Lanczos approach and provides a poor filter.
[src:fsr-upscaling/lanczos-resampling] There are many better single-lobe, bell-shaped windowing functions.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] Aliasing is manifested in the case of 2D images as moiré pattern and pixelated edges, colloquially known as "jaggies".
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] Common signal processing and image processing knowledge suggests that to achieve perfect elimination of aliasing, proper spatial sampling at the Nyquist rate (or higher) after applying a 2D Anti-aliasing filter is required.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] As this approach would require a forward and inverse fourier transformation, computationally less demanding approximations like supersampling were developed to avoid domain switches by staying in the spatial domain ("image domain").
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] Supersampling is computationally expensive because it requires much greater video card memory and memory bandwidth, since the amount of buffer used is several times larger.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] A way around this problem is to use a technique known as **adaptive supersampling**, where only pixels at the edges of objects are supersampled.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] Initially only a few samples are taken within each pixel.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] If these values are very similar, only these samples are used to determine the color.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] The result of this method is that a higher number of samples are calculated only where necessary, thus improving performance.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] When taking samples within a pixel, the sample positions have to be determined in some way.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] Although the number of ways in which this can be done is infinite, there are a few ways which are commonly used.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] The pixel is split into several sub-pixels, and a sample is taken from the center of each.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] Although, due to the regular nature of sampling, aliasing can still occur if a low number of sub-pixels is used.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] Also known as stochastic sampling, it avoids the regularity of grid supersampling.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] However, due to the irregularity of the pattern, samples end up being unnecessary in some areas of the pixel and lacking in others.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] The Poisson disk sampling algorithm places the samples randomly, but then checks that any two are not too close.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] The end result is an even but random distribution of samples.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] The naive "dart throwing" algorithm is extremely slow for large data sets, which once limited its applications for real-time rendering.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] However, many fast algorithms now exist to generate Poisson disk noise, even those with variable density.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] The Delone set provides a mathematical description of such sampling.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] A modification of the grid algorithm to approximate the Poisson disk.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] A pixel is split into several sub-pixels, but a sample is not taken from the center of each, but from a random point within the sub-pixel.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] Congregation can still occur, but to a lesser degree.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] A 2×2 grid layout is used but the sample pattern is rotated to avoid samples aligning on the horizontal or vertical axis, greatly improving antialiasing quality for the most commonly encountered cases.
[src:fsr-upscaling/supersampling] For an optimal pattern, the rotation angle is arctan (⁠1/2⁠) (about 26.6°) and the square is stretched by a factor of ⁠√5/2⁠, making it also a 4-queens solution.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] Video scalers are typically found inside consumer electronics devices such as televisions, video game consoles, and DVD or Blu-ray players, but can also be found in other AV equipment (such as video editing and television broadcasting equipment).
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] Video scalers can also be completely separate devices, often providing simple video switching capabilities.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] These units are commonly found as part of home theatre or projected presentation systems.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] They are often combined with other video processing devices or algorithms to create a video processor that improves the apparent definition of video signals.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] Video scalers are primarily a digital device; however, they can be combined with an analog-to-digital converter (ADC, or digitizer) and a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) to support analog inputs and outputs.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] The native resolution of a display is how many physical pixels make up each row and column of the visible area on the display's output surface.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] There are many different video signals in use which are not the same resolution (neither are all of the displays), thus some form of resolution adaptation is required to properly frame a video signal to a display device.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] For example, within the United States, there are NTSC, ATSC, and VESA video standards, each with several different resolution video formats.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] Multiple common resolutions are also used for high-definition television; 720p, 1080i, and 1080p.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] While scaling a video signal does allow it to match the size of a particular display, the process can result in an increased number of visual artifacts in the signal, such as ringing and posterization.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] Television channels that air a mixture of 16:9 high-definition programming and 4:3 standard definition programming may employ scaling or cropping in order to make the programming fill the entire screen, as opposed to pillarboxing the feed instead, in order to maintain consistency in format.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] Likewise, broadcasters downscale programming produced in 16:9 for broadcast on their 4:3 feeds through letterboxing—either as a full 16:9 letterbox, or a partial 14:9 letterbox—a technique used primarily by European broadcasters during the transition to digital terrestrial television.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] When the U.S. cable network TNT introduced an HD feed in 2004, it controversially employed a stretching system known as FlexView (which was also offered to other broadcasters).
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] FlexView used a nonlinear method to stretch more near the edges of the screen than in the center of it.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] The practice was imposed by the senior vice president of broadcast engineering at TNT, Clyde D.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] Smith, who argued that pillarboxing led to inconsistency between programs for viewers, could cause burn-in on plasma televisions, some older HDTVs could not stretch 4:3 content automatically, and the quality of stretching on some displays was poor.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] Despite TNT's intentions, the system was frequently criticized by viewers of high definition channels, with some nicknaming the effect "Stretch-O-Vision".
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] In 2014, FXX faced similar criticism for its use of cropping and scaling on reruns of *The Simpsons* (which only started producing episodes in HD beginning in its 20th season), as its cropping method caused various visual gags to be lost.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] In February 2015, FXX announced that in response to these complaints, it would present these episodes in their original 4:3 aspect ratio on its video-on-demand service.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] Some series that were originally shot on 35 mm film—such as *Friends* and *Seinfeld*—have been converted to high-definition by cropping a widescreen image from the 4-perf pulldown.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] In 2023, video upscaling products using generative artificial intelligence were previewed or released, such as NVIDIA's Video Super Resolution and Adobe's Project Res-Up.
[src:fsr-upscaling/video-scaler] Unlike previous upscaling systems, these technologies generated new data based on provided video frames.
